name: Go Tell It on the Mountain

Main Title [Singin' in the Rain]
comments: Brief opening credits version as performed by the 1952 film's three stars. This album's track (titled only as "Main Title") is the earliest commercial release that could be located for this version; the more famous solo version of Singin' in the Rain by Gene Kelly has been available since 1952. After the vocals, the MGM Studio Orchestra segues into an instrumental version of You Are My Lucky Star for the remainder of the track.

name: Tango (Temptation)
comments: Brief instrumental version featured in the 1952 film, but not released until this expanded soundtrack release.

name: Would You?
comments: Recorded for the 1952 film, but previously unreleased. In the film, Noyes provided Debbie Reynolds' singing voice for this track, ironically intended for a scene in which Reynolds' character was supposed to be providing a vocal track for the character played by Jean Hagen to lip-synch to!

name: Singin' in the Rain (in A-Flat)
comments: Solo performance from the end of the film, previously unreleased.

comments: This track is only named "The Love Medley" on the album with no specifics on the medley parts, however, I have identified them.  The medley opens and closes with "Love Will Keep Us Together" and in between are "How Sweet It Is to Be Loved by You", then "You Are So Beautiful", then "Sunshine on My Shoulders" and then "Just Too Many People".
